events.description: Baghdad is founded.
events.html: • 762 – Baghdad is founded.

events.description: First Defenestration of Prague: A crowd of radical Hussites kill seven members of the Prague city council.
events.html: • 1419 – First Defenestration of Prague: A crowd of radical Hussites kill seven members of the Prague city council.

events.description: Christopher Columbus lands at Guanaja in the Bay Islands off the coast of Honduras during his fourth voyage.
events.html: • 1502 – Christopher Columbus lands at Guanaja in the Bay Islands off the coast of Honduras during his fourth voyage.

events.description: Beaver Wars: At Ticonderoga (now Crown Point, New York), Samuel de Champlain shoots and kills two Iroquois chiefs on behalf of his native allies.
events.html: • 1609 – Beaver Wars: At Ticonderoga (now Crown Point, New York), Samuel de Champlain shoots and kills two Iroquois chiefs on behalf of his native allies.

events.description: In Jamestown, Virginia, the first Colonial European representative assembly in the Americas, the Virginia General Assembly, convenes for the first time.
events.html: • 1619 – In Jamestown, Virginia, the first Colonial European representative assembly in the Americas, the Virginia General Assembly, convenes for the first time.

events.description: An earthquake kills about 5,000 people in Gargano, Italy.
events.html: • 1627 – An earthquake kills about 5,000 people in Gargano, Italy.[1]

events.description: Eighty Years' War: The Siege of Schenkenschans begins; Frederick Henry, Prince of Orange, begins the recapture of the strategically important fortress from the Spanish Army.
events.html: • 1635 – Eighty Years' War: The Siege of Schenkenschans begins; Frederick Henry, Prince of Orange, begins the recapture of the strategically important fortress from the Spanish Army.

events.description: English Civil War: Scottish Covenanter forces under the Earl of Leven launch the Siege of Hereford, a remaining Royalist stronghold.
events.html: • 1645 – English Civil War: Scottish Covenanter forces under the Earl of Leven launch the Siege of Hereford, a remaining Royalist stronghold.[2]

events.description: The Battle of Warsaw ends with a Swedish-Brandenburger victory over a larger Polish-Lithuanian force.
events.html: • 1656 – The Battle of Warsaw ends with a Swedish-Brandenburger victory over a larger Polish-Lithuanian force.

events.description: Nathaniel Bacon issues the "Declaration of the People of Virginia", beginning Bacon's Rebellion against the rule of Governor William Berkeley.
events.html: • 1676 – Nathaniel Bacon issues the "Declaration of the People of Virginia", beginning Bacon's Rebellion against the rule of Governor William Berkeley.

events.description: Founding of Baltimore, Maryland.
events.html: • 1729 – Founding of Baltimore, Maryland.

events.description: The first Masonic Grand Lodge in the future United States is constituted in Massachusetts.
events.html: • 1733 – The first Masonic Grand Lodge in the future United States is constituted in Massachusetts.

events.description: In Saint Petersburg, Bartolomeo Rastrelli presents the newly built Catherine Palace to Empress Elizabeth and her courtiers.
events.html: • 1756 – In Saint Petersburg, Bartolomeo Rastrelli presents the newly built Catherine Palace to Empress Elizabeth and her courtiers.

events.description: Father Miguel Hidalgo y Costilla, leader of the Mexican insurgency, is executed by the Spanish in Chihuahua City, Mexico.
events.html: • 1811 – Father Miguel Hidalgo y Costilla, leader of the Mexican insurgency, is executed by the Spanish in Chihuahua City, Mexico.

events.description: First ascent of Grand Combin, one of the highest summits in the Alps.
events.html: • 1859 – First ascent of Grand Combin, one of the highest summits in the Alps.

events.description: American Indian Wars: Representatives of the United States and tribal leaders including Chief Pocatello (of the Shoshone)  sign the Treaty of Box Elder.
events.html: • 1863 – American Indian Wars: Representatives of the United States and tribal leaders including Chief Pocatello (of the Shoshone) sign the Treaty of Box Elder.

events.description: Valuev Circular banned the publication of religious, educational and training books in Ukrainian in the Russian Empire.
events.html: • 1863 – Valuev Circular banned the publication of religious, educational and training books in Ukrainian in the Russian Empire.[3]

events.description: American Civil War: Battle of the Crater: Union forces attempt to break Confederate lines at Petersburg, Virginia by exploding a large bomb under their trenches.
events.html: • 1864 – American Civil War: Battle of the Crater: Union forces attempt to break Confederate lines at Petersburg, Virginia by exploding a large bomb under their trenches.

events.description: The steamboat Brother Jonathan sinks off the coast of Crescent City, California, killing 225 passengers, the deadliest shipwreck on the Pacific Coast of the U.S. at the time.
events.html: • 1865 – The steamboat Brother Jonathan sinks off the coast of Crescent City, California, killing 225 passengers, the deadliest shipwreck on the Pacific Coast of the U.S. at the time.

events.description: Armed Confederate veterans in New Orleans riot against a meeting of Radical Republicans, killing 48 people and injuring another 100.
events.html: • 1866 – Armed Confederate veterans in New Orleans riot against a meeting of Radical Republicans, killing 48 people and injuring another 100.

events.description: The Staten Island Ferry Westfield's boiler explodes, killing over 85 people.
events.html: • 1871 – The Staten Island Ferry Westfield's boiler explodes, killing over 85 people.

events.description: Japan's Emperor Meiji dies and is succeeded by his son Yoshihito, who is now known as the Emperor Taishō.
events.html: • 1912 – Japan's Emperor Meiji dies and is succeeded by his son Yoshihito, who is now known as the Emperor Taishō.

events.description: The Black Tom explosion in New York Harbor kills four and destroys some $20,000,000 worth of military goods.
events.html: • 1916 – The Black Tom explosion in New York Harbor kills four and destroys some $20,000,000 worth of military goods.[4]

events.description: In Montevideo, Uruguay wins the first FIFA World Cup by beating Argentina.
events.html: • 1930 – In Montevideo, Uruguay wins the first FIFA World Cup by beating Argentina.[5]

events.description: Premiere of Walt Disney's Flowers and Trees, the first cartoon short to use Technicolor and the first Academy Award winning cartoon short.
events.html: • 1932 – Premiere of Walt Disney's Flowers and Trees,[6] the first cartoon short to use Technicolor[7] and the first Academy Award winning cartoon short.[8]

entities.name: Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film

events.description: World War II: Japanese submarine I-58 sinks the USS Indianapolis, killing 883 seamen. Most die during the following four days, until an aircraft notices the survivors.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: Japanese submarine I-58 sinks the USS Indianapolis, killing 883 seamen. Most die during the following four days, until an aircraft notices the survivors.

events.description: A joint resolution of the U.S. Congress is signed by President Dwight D. Eisenhower, authorizing In God We Trust as the U.S. national motto.
events.html: • 1956 – A joint resolution of the U.S. Congress is signed by President Dwight D. Eisenhower, authorizing In God We Trust as the U.S. national motto.

events.description: The Trans-Canada Highway, the then longest national highway in the world, is officially opened.
events.html: • 1962 – The Trans-Canada Highway, the then longest national highway in the world, is officially opened.

events.description: U.S. President Lyndon B. Johnson signs the Social Security Act of 1965 into law, establishing Medicare and Medicaid.
events.html: • 1965 – U.S. President Lyndon B. Johnson signs the Social Security Act of 1965 into law, establishing Medicare and Medicaid.

events.description: England defeats West Germany to win the 1966 FIFA World Cup at Wembley Stadium after extra time.
events.html: • 1966 – England defeats West Germany to win the 1966 FIFA World Cup at Wembley Stadium after extra time.

events.description: Vietnam War: US President Richard Nixon makes an unscheduled visit to South Vietnam and meets with President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu and U.S. military commanders.
events.html: • 1969 – Vietnam War: US President Richard Nixon makes an unscheduled visit to South Vietnam and meets with President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu and U.S. military commanders.

events.description: Apollo program: On Apollo 15, David Scott and James Irwin in the Apollo Lunar Module Falcon land on the Moon with the first Lunar Rover.
events.html: • 1971 – Apollo program: On Apollo 15, David Scott and James Irwin in the Apollo Lunar Module Falcon land on the Moon with the first Lunar Rover.

events.description: An All Nippon Airways Boeing 727 and a Japanese Air Force F-86 collide over Morioka, Iwate, Japan killing 162.
events.html: • 1971 – An All Nippon Airways Boeing 727 and a Japanese Air Force F-86 collide over Morioka, Iwate, Japan killing 162.

events.description: Watergate scandal: U.S. President Richard Nixon releases subpoenaed White House recordings after being ordered to do so by the Supreme Court of the United States.
events.html: • 1974 – Watergate scandal: U.S. President Richard Nixon releases subpoenaed White House recordings after being ordered to do so by the Supreme Court of the United States.

entities.name: Supreme Court of the United States

events.description: Jimmy Hoffa disappears from the parking lot of the Machus Red Fox restaurant in Bloomfield Hills, Michigan, a suburb of Detroit, at about 2:30 p.m. He is never seen or heard from again.
events.html: • 1975 – Jimmy Hoffa disappears from the parking lot of the Machus Red Fox restaurant in Bloomfield Hills, Michigan, a suburb of Detroit, at about 2:30 p.m. He is never seen or heard from again.

events.description: The 730: Okinawa Prefecture changes its traffic on the right-hand side of the road to the left-hand side.
events.html: • 1978 – The 730: Okinawa Prefecture changes its traffic on the right-hand side of the road to the left-hand side.

events.description: Vanuatu gains independence.
events.html: • 1980 – Vanuatu gains independence.

events.description: Israel's Knesset passes the Jerusalem Law.
events.html: • 1980 – Israel's Knesset passes the Jerusalem Law.

events.description: As many as 50,000 demonstrators, mostly women and children, took to the streets in Łódź to protest food ration shortages in Communist Poland.
events.html: • 1981 – As many as 50,000 demonstrators, mostly women and children, took to the streets in Łódź to protest food ration shortages in Communist Poland.

events.description: Ian Gow, Conservative Member of Parliament, is assassinated at his home by the IRA in a car bombing after he assured the group that the British government would never surrender to them.
events.html: • 1990 – Ian Gow, Conservative Member of Parliament, is assassinated at his home by the IRA in a car bombing after he assured the group that the British government would never surrender to them.[9]

events.description: In Mexico, the last 'old style' Volkswagen Beetle rolls off the assembly line.
events.html: • 2003 – In Mexico, the last 'old style' Volkswagen Beetle rolls off the assembly line.

events.description: Three years after the death the last Pyrenean ibex, Celia, a clone of her is born only to subsequently die from lung defects. Within minutes, the Pyrenean ibex becomes the first and so-far only species to have ever gone de-extinct as well as go extinct twice.
events.html: • 2003 – Three years after the death the last Pyrenean ibex, Celia, a clone of her is born only to subsequently die from lung defects. Within minutes, the Pyrenean ibex becomes the first and so-far only species to have ever gone de-extinct as well as go extinct twice.[10][11]

events.description: The world's longest running music show Top of the Pops is broadcast for the last time on BBC Two. The show had aired for 42 years.
events.html: • 2006 – The world's longest running music show Top of the Pops is broadcast for the last time on BBC Two. The show had aired for 42 years.

events.description: An Israeli airstrike kills 28 Lebanese civilians, including 16 children.
events.html: • 2006 – An Israeli airstrike kills 28 Lebanese civilians, including 16 children.[12]

events.description: Marriage of Queen Elizabeth II's eldest granddaughter Zara Phillips to former rugby union footballer Mike Tindall.
events.html: • 2011 – Marriage of Queen Elizabeth II's eldest granddaughter Zara Phillips to former rugby union footballer Mike Tindall.
